 that set in following the Great Recession of 2008. Paying careful attention to government expenditures and budgetary politics, Bolukbasi analyses the political economy of reform in countries where the EMU’s impact was expected to be greatest. Based on in-depth comparative case studies of Belgium, Greece, and Italy, he shows how scholars, policymakers, and citizens alike expected Euro-austerity to erode Europe’s welfare states. Contrary to popular opinion, Bolukbasi finds that the reality was much more complicated. A thorough critique of the "Euro-austerity hypothesis," this book presents a rigorous comparative study of the resilience of the welfare state in various national contexts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aBelgium-Appropriations and expenditures-Case studies. 0aWelfare statezBelgiumvCase studies. 0aWelfare statezGreecevCase studies. 0aWelfare statezItalyvCase studies. 0aWelfare state-Belgium-Case studies. 0aWelfare state-Greece-Case studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aBelgium.  aEuro-austerity.  aEurope.  aGreat Recession.  aGreece.  aItaly.  aMaastricht Treaty.  aausterity.  aeconomics.  ainternational relations.  areform.  awelfare state.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2021 Englishz978311075417908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2021z9783110753943oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073922040uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753689340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/97